Rules of Back-gammon. You see there not MY rules!

I will say for instance that you are the RED team Playing the BLUE 
team. Just before the game starts you will be shown who is playing 
and which side you are on ie RED vs. BLUE. You see from this example
RED's Bank is on the left.


1)  You have to get all your pieces (Mushies!) across the board to 
the other side (Bank on the right, Blue Bank). Your Bank is 
shown by the Hut with your colour on it (Red). His is marked in Blue.

2)  You can only move your pieces to the right (In this Example) and 
he can only move to the left.

3)  You take it in turns to roll the dice. There are only two dice and 
you have to use these numbers independently ie. One at a time. You 
cannot add them together but you CAN move the same piece twice! 
This sounds like the same thing doesn't it. Let's say for example you 
threw a 4 and 3 and you couldn't move 4 or 3, but you could move 
7, this is not allowed! You have to use one dice at a time!

4)  Now how do you move and what can't you do! You can move any 
piece to anywhere on the board as long as there is a space for it. 
You can also move and land on another players piece as long as 
there is just one piece there! When this happens that piece will go 
back to his hut and have to start his 'trip' again. So you see from 
this that it is important not to leave one piece by itself.

5)  If you have a piece on the bank, you can only move that piece. It
has to be moved before you can start moving any other pieces. If you
can't move it eg. all possible moves are blocked by the other player
you will miss a go!

6)  You will have to use all you dice up unless you can't make a legal 
move. You can't give up your go, just because you would leave yourself
open. You must use ALL dice if at all possible! 

7)  Now, I said at the start that you have to get onto the other 
players 'bank'. Well there is one limitation here, and that is you can't 
take any pieces off until ALL your pieces are past the last 'POST' or 
to put it another way in the last 6 places. 

8)  When taking your pieces off you must use whole moves, eg. if you 
were in the second to last 'place' or (Island) and you throw a 2, you 
can move that piece off. you could however move one of the other 
pieces, accept the piece on the last place because that would waste a 
move. the only time you can waste moves is when there are NO 
higher placed pieces, eg. if you threw a 6 and you had a piece on the 
'5th to last' place and you didn't have a piece on '6th to last' place 
then you are allowed to move him. 

9)  The game is ended when one player gets all pieces off the board.

10) There are three types of 'win' and they are:-

   Back Gammon 3pts   The other player still has pieces in his half. 
   Gammon      2pts   The other player has passed half way but has
                       not moved any pieces off the board.
   Won          1pt   The other player has started to take off his
                       own pieces.

11) Extra Options.

As well as the rules above there are some optional rules:-

Limit.  (Default's to 5)

This is a limit to the amount of pieces that can be stacked on top of 
each other. Some people have this set to 5 and some people turn it 
off.

Bonus.   (Default is double)

When you throw two of the same number with the dice it is classed 
as being 4 of the same. eg. 2 + 2 will become 2 + 2 + 2 + 2. Most 
people use this system but if you want you can turn it off. It might 
make the game last longer and it will take out some of the luck 
element (Random Factor!).

These settings can be changed from the main menu and also just 
before a game! Select the RULES button to change the options.

This is where I would like to here some suggestions for improvements. 
If you play Back gammon with different settings then let me know and 
I will add your ideas to the game.

Well that's the rules sorted out. This document was written straight 
from memory and I might of missed some rules out. Also some 
people play with slightly different rules so let me know!

